The events tested the mettle of our nation and its structures. We came to know our health systems better. Our education sector would be brought to an abrupt shutdown, thanks to its reliance on the brick-and-mortar in-person mode of delivery.
Firms closed down, since most were client-facing ventures. First came the hospitality industry, as flights got grounded. The entertainment industry followed. Eventually, all non-essential service providers would either be furloughed or sent home for good. It was the worst scene in a horror movie.





But against all these came myriads of lessons. As a country, we learned that a time could come when each nation would be by itself, with none looking to the other for rescue. We would reckon how critical it was for each to establish strong systems, more so economically, such that we would survive, albeit for a while, without flying out or expecting manna from foreigners. We equally learned that the devil never sleeps, as evidenced by those who stole resources allocated towards management of Covid-19. Indeed, corruption knows no seasons.
Urban-rural migration
We learned how strategic devolution was. It was not lost on us how the rural folks came to the aid of the urbanites, seeing the voluminous foodstuffs that were ferried to towns and cities in a bid to rescue those who had either lost livelihoods or were caught up in lockdowns. We also witnessed urban-rural migration, for the centre that is our urban cities could not hold. Without a doubt, devolved units must be made fully functional.



